node.text: ADOPTABLE: Edward Milo, Lab mix (5 y/o), at @water4dogsnyc – Tribeca, NYC. Available via @camphappytailsnycrescue • “He was once a normal, able bodied, healthy dog. He loved running all day on his family’s ranch in Texas. Like a true southern boy, he’d always be home for supper. One day, he just didn’t return. They searched for him, and when they found him he was wailing and his back legs weren’t working. Sadly his original owners did him a disservice – the first 48 hours are crucial for dog spinal injuries like his. If he was able to get medical attention sooner, perhaps the damage could’ve been reversed. After that, he was put in a kill shelter. No one wanted to adopt him, being a large paralyzed dog with medical issues. We swooped in on the day he was set to be euthanized and took him in. It’s been a lot of work. The first couple of months he would spend six days a week here getting therapy. His legs need to be expressed nine times a day, he eats a special diet, he gets massages so his muscles don’t atrophy, red light treatment to stimulate cells, and he does water therapy, which he looks forward to so much. He’s got such a ‘pull yourself up by your bootstraps’ attitude. He’s such an inspiration and he’s one of our favorite campers of all time.”

node.text: Oakley, Landseer Newfoundland (4 y/o; @that_nepa_newfie), Tobyhanna Lake – Poconos, PA • “She’s a water rescue dog, trained at the American Academy of Canine Water Rescue in Boston, MA. She started training at 11-weeks old and is level two, meaning she can deploy from land and water from a boat. The third level is being able to deploy from a helicopter, which we’re working on. Everything about the Newfoundland is designed for water rescue – fully webbed paws, they do a breast-stroke like a human (instead of a doggy-paddle), and they’re a dual-coat breed that can work in freezing arctic waters. She can break through the ice on our lake. There was actually a Newfoundland on the Titanic that swam for miles pulling a lifeboat. She can pull 50 times her weight in the water – you can daisy-chain 6-7 people in one shot. The goggles protect her eyes from impacts like sticks in the forest – the lenses get a lot of scratches. She acts as a second lifeguard with you, never on her own. She’s never had to rescue anyone yet, but we’re planning to patrol the beaches when we go to Italy for helicopter training with the Italian School of Water Rescue Dogs. It’s very common in Italy that dogs are with lifeguards on the beach. She’s been on helicopters here, which is like walking into a hurricane – most dogs won’t do that. We’re doing all of this to prevent drowning deaths – what better a cause than to save a life. There’s never any reason to drown and it’s in her natural instincts to save you from doing so. Water work is different. Any dog can swim – there's a difference between saving themselves versus looking to save someone else. She’ll drown herself saving you. She wants to save you. To me, that's priceless. If we ever prevented one person from drowning that would be a life goal. We go to schools and teach kids water safety – it’s easier to prevent it from happening. The goal is to never have to get in the water to save someone.” @that_nepa_newfie

node.text: Tugboat, Labrador Retriever (4 m/o), Cotuit, MA • “We call her our little wildling – she’s a whirlwind of chaos but we couldn’t love her more. Tug will become my second medical alert and PTSD service dog. The training has already started and it’s an all day, exhausting practice, especially on top of all the work I already have to do to manage my dissociations and PTSD flashbacks. I have a curriculum and professional trainer that we work with. It’s critical that she’s properly trained – my freedom and health depend on it . A lot of people ask if Waffle is retiring now that we’ve got Tugboat. I don’t know when she will retire, but giving her the choice to work or not and the knowledge that she can eventually retire and rest with the peace of mind that I will still be cared for is everything.” @wafflenugget
